# The Bark

A vocal repertoire shaped by living with humans.

<!-- pause -->

- Frequency range: **subwoofer to small-dog-stress (50–2000 Hz)**
<!-- pause -->
- Adult dogs bark in contexts adult wolves rarely do — domestication selected for vocal communication with us
<!-- pause -->
- A bark is **a whole sentence**: pitch carries identity, tempo carries urgency, repetition carries persistence

<!-- note: Compare to cats: cats invented the meow specifically for humans. Dogs already vocalized; domestication tuned the frequency. Both species adjusted their voices for us. -->
<!-- comment(@reviewer): cite Yin & McCowan 2004 for the "barks carry identity" claim. -->
<!-- ai: comment intentionally left here to test the comments panel + per-deck filtering. The Yin & McCowan paper is real but the rest of the slide is talk-grade summary. -->

