# Dog Communication

Dogs use a multi-channel vocabulary humans only partially decode.

<!-- pause -->

| Signal       | Meaning                          | Audience       |
|--------------|----------------------------------|----------------|
| Bark         | Many things — depends on context | Humans + dogs  |
| Tail wag (R) | Generally positive (right-bias)  | Humans + dogs  |
| Tail wag (L) | Generally cautious (left-bias)   | Humans + dogs  |
| Play bow     | "What follows is play"           | Other dogs     |
| Whale eye    | "I'm uncomfortable, back off"    | Anyone close   |
| Yawn         | Stress (NOT sleepiness here)     | Humans         |

<!-- pause -->

> Tail wag asymmetry is real and replicable: dogs wag more to the right when seeing their owner, more to the left when seeing an unfamiliar dominant dog (Quaranta et al. 2007).

<!-- note: The tail asymmetry slide always gets a "wait, really?" reaction. Make sure the blockquote stays on screen long enough to read. -->

