# The Math of Loyalty

A toy model.

```
loyalty = (years_known × shared_meals) / interruptions²
```

<!-- pause -->

Where:

- `years_known` accumulates linearly
- `shared_meals` includes any food the dog watched you eat
- `interruptions` is the only term you can hurt — unexpected boarding, long absences, schedule chaos

<!-- pause -->

> The denominator is squared because dogs feel disruption more sharply than absence. A predictable life with less time together beats a chaotic life with more.

---variant: loyalty-equation-tighter
# The Loyalty Equation

```
loyalty = (time × meals) / chaos²
```

Three terms. The denominator is the one to manage.

---variant: loyalty-equation-no-math
# Why Routine Matters

Dogs love you proportional to the time you've shared. They worry proportional to how unpredictable you are. Routine is how you maximize one and minimize the other.

<!-- ai: 2 variants on slide 9, mirroring cats.slides:9 (which has 2 variants on the cuteness equation). The "tighter" variant compresses the math; the "no-math" variant drops the equation entirely. test variant switching + side-by-side compare here, and verify the cross-deck UI shows BOTH cats:9 and dogs:9 variants when navigating with the deck switcher. -->

